Verified verbatim against darktable master (raw.githubusercontent.com/darktable-org/darktable/master/src/common/locallaplacian.c, function `curve_scalar`, lines 313-343 — line numbers exactly as cited, last modified 2025-02-03 per GitHub commit history):

```c
static inline float curve_scalar(
    const float x,
    const float g,
    const float sigma,
    const float shadows,
    const float highlights,
    const float clarity)
{
  const float c = x-g;
  float val;
  // blend in via quadratic bezier
  if     (c >  2*sigma) val = g + sigma + shadows    * (c-sigma);
  else if(c < -2*sigma) val = g - sigma + highlights * (c+sigma);
  else if(c > 0.0f)
  { // shadow contrast
    const float t = CLAMPS(c / (2.0f*sigma), 0.0f, 1.0f);
    const float t2 = t * t;
    const float mt = 1.0f-t;
    val = g + sigma * 2.0f*mt*t + t2*(sigma + sigma*shadows);
  }
  else
  { // highlight contrast
    const float t = CLAMPS(-c / (2.0f*sigma), 0.0f, 1.0f);
    const float t2 = t * t;
    const float mt = 1.0f-t;
    val = g - sigma * 2.0f*mt*t + t2*(- sigma - sigma*highlights);
  }
  // midtone local contrast
  val += clarity * c * dt_fast_expf(-c*c/(2.0f*sigma*sigma/3.0f));
  return val;
}
```
Called from `apply_curve()` (line 363) as `curve_scalar(*(in2++), g, sigma, shadows, highlights, clarity)` where `in2` is the fine Gaussian-pyramid pixel (absolute intensity) and `g` is the coarse/gamma-reference level (absolute intensity) — so c = x-g is confirmed to be the absolute-domain detail residual, not a pre-normalized value.
